entry.title: Revert "Flags UI: Remove jstemplate."
entry.content:
This reverts commit 13a42b4af1cfb3e08725bb6634b89bdf5d85d261.



Reason for revert: It is breaking chrome://flags on iOS.



Original change's description:

> Flags UI: Remove jstemplate.

>

> jstemplate is deprecated and no longer used. This CL removes

> its usage in chrome://flags, which also makes the page less

> wasteful while rendering content.

>

> The template rendering strategy attached all available experiments into

> the DOM twice, one in a section for non-default experiments and one in a

> section for default experiments. It then toggled the visibility of each

> element depending on whether it was default or non-default.

>

> This approach instead only attaches each experiment to its respective

> section depending on its status as default. Therefore, no extra elements

> need to be attached and toggled to 'hidden'.

>

> This CL brings the time it takes to render experiments down from

> 1.5s to 1.25s on Linux.

>

entry.title: Fix carets placed in non-editable elements due to collapsed whitespace
entry.content:
https://crrev.com/c/3257487 and https://crrev.com/c/3620254 previously

made it so a caret inside an editable element couldn't cross into a

contained non-editable element as a result of adjusting the visually

equivalent position, when using `kCannotCrossEditingBoundary`.

However, in some cases involving collapsed whitespace between the

editing boundary and the edge of the editable element, the caret could

still cross into the non-editable element.



When the `MostForwardCaretPosition` and `MostBackwardCaretPosition`

functions are called with `kCannotCrossEditingBoundary`, they are

supposed to prevent crossing the editing boundary: the returned

position must be either null or have the same editability as the input

position. This is achieved by checking whether the anchor node at each

iterated position has the same editability as the previous one.



However, when the input position is beforeAnchor or afterAnchor, the

editability of the position might not be the same as the editability

of its anchor node. This is not checked, and thus it allows smuggling

an editing boundary before the check starts.



This patch fixes this by setting `start_editable` to whether the

position's container node is editable, rather than its anchor node,

if we are preventing crossing editable boundaries and allowing

snapping to the edges of inline nodes. `last_node` is similarly set to

the position's container node to detect if the first iterated position

has changed editability.



This bug was also causing an endless loop in cases where the

non-editable element contains an

crossing over into the non-editable element and it tries to position

itself inside the SVG, but

cannot find any valid position.

entry.title: [@scope] Avoid invalidation flags based on in_rightmost_compound
entry.content:
When matching selectors against certain pseudo-classes,

we set flags to indicate that elements depend on those

pseudo-classes. To distinguish between elements that depend on

a pseudo-class directly and elements that are *related* to such

a dependency, we use the in_rightmost_compound flag.



This does not work well with @scope and the StyleScopeFrame cache,

because we evaluate the selectors in the @scope prelude *once*,

when the scope activations are first calculated. At that time,

:scope will either be in the subject position

(in_rightmost_compound=true), *or* in the non-subject position

(in_rightmost_compound=false), and the invalidation flags will be

marked accordingly. If we're matching another scoped selector later

with :scope in the opposite position, we'll hit the cache,

and neglect to set the flags we need.



In preparation of solving this problem, this CL introduces

"impact" to SelectorCheckingContext, which controls directly how

flags should be set. The critical difference between this and

in_rightmost_compound is that it's possible to specify impact=kBoth,

which will cause *both* subject/non-subject flags to set. This will

be used by @scope in a future CL.

entry.title: [a11y] Use CComSingleThreadModel for a11y COM objects
entry.content:
Accessible objects live and die on the UI thread, so it is safe to use

`CComSingleThreadModel` rather than `CComMultiThreadModel`. This has two

benefits:



1. It removes the locking overhead on calls to `AddRef` and `Release`.

2. It shrinks the size of each instance by the size of a

`CComCriticalSection` (48 bytes for a 64-bit build).

entry.title: [wayland] Keep Output state consistent when propagating notifications
entry.content:
This CL updates OnOutputRemoved() such that both display_id_map_ and

display_list_ are updated at the same time after a new primary

display has been set.



Currently we are hitting an error condition where the display is

removed from the display_id_map_ first, then the primary display

is updated, then it is removed from display_list_.



As clients respond to the change of primary display, they may call

back into WaylandScreen and end up hitting DCHECKs/CHECKs due to

inconsistency between the two structures.



Specifically this was happening when updating the primary

display in OnOutputRemoved(). Clients could end up calling into

WaylandWindow::GetPreferredEnteredOutputId(), which had the

potential to check the state of display_list_.

entry.title: Use LayerDelegate to draw aura touch selection handles.
entry.content:
Currently, TouchHandleDrawableAura uses ImageWindowDelegate to draw

touch selection handle images. It is also the only place that still uses

ImageWindowDelegate (probably due to refactors over the years).



Most of the logic in ImageWindowDelegate doesn't seem to be needed

anymore, e.g. background_color_ is always set as transparent, so we

don't actually need background_color_ or size_mismatch_. To simplify

things, make TouchHandleDrawableAura a LayerDelegate that draws the

touch handles and then delete ImageWindowDelegate.



(This is mostly just some cleanup ahead of some changes we'd like to

make to the touch handle styling.)
